What's actually happening in the SERPs
The big picture: the head terms are locked. carsales, CarsGuide, Drive, CarExpert, ReDriven, and australiancar.reviews dominate any "[make] [model] review" query. ReDriven is particularly relevant for you because they specifically own the "common faults / used car buyer's guide" angle and they've built it on YouTube + site authority. Beating them on their core models is hard.
But there are exploitable gaps, specifically in three places:

Less-reviewed models that are still selling in volume — particularly the new Chinese brands (Chery, GWM, BYD, MG, Geely, Jaecoo) where the established review sites don't have years of accumulated authority and ReDriven's "common faults" angle literally can't exist yet because the cars are too new.
State/region-specific buyer queries — "[model] for WA conditions," "best 4WD for Pilbara work," "[model] in Perth." Big sites write nationally; local angles are wide open.
Specific used-buyer scenarios — "best year for the [model]," "[model] vs [model] for tradies," "should I buy a [year] [model] in 2026" — these are conversion-ready buyer-intent queries that the big sites don't always target with dedicated pages.

