How I'd actually point the MCP at this
Don't write 30 reviews and dump them. Index in waves so you can see what works:
Wave 1 (week 1): Tier 1 reviews 1-5 (Chery, Haval, MG, BYD, Outlander). New-brand angle is the highest-leverage. If these index in 4-6 weeks, your domain has authority potential.
Wave 2 (week 3): Tier 1 reviews 6-10 + Tier 2 reviews 11-13. Mix of buyer-intent and tradie angles.
Wave 3 (week 6): Whatever else based on what indexed. Double down on whichever Tier worked.
Each review should target the specific buyer query not the generic model name. Title formula:

[Model] Common Problems and Best Year to Buy in 2026 (Australian Buyer's Guide)
Is the [Model] Worth Buying Used in 2026? Honest Australian Review
[Model] vs [Competitor] for Tradies — Which Used Ute Wins?

One honest caveat
Even at 30 reviews indexed, expect 3-6 months before any meaningful traffic, and the realistic ceiling for a brand-new domain in this space is maybe 5,000-15,000 monthly visits in year one if you execute well. That's $20-100/mo of AdSense plus whatever CarVertical and parts affiliates pull. Worth doing for the cost of MCP runs and your dormant domain — but don't expect viral.
The Chery Tiggo 4 review is genuinely your best single shot. It's selling like crazy, almost no one has deep used-buyer content on it yet, and ReDriven hasn't owned the SERP. If I could only point your MCP at one car, that's the one.